 England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tilley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Tilly-sur-Seulles (Calvados) or Tilly (Eure), France.","English: habitational name from Tyley in Wotton under Edge (Gloucestershire), Tiley in Minterne Magna (Dorset), or Tilley (Shropshire). The Gloucestershire and Dorset placenames derive from Old English <i>tigel</i> ‘tile’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, woodland clearing’. The Shropshire placename derives from an uncertain first element + Old English <i>lēah</i>.","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>tilie</i> ‘one who tills the land, a husbandman’. Compare   Tiller  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Tillie","meanings":["English (northern England and southern Scotland): variant of   Tilley  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Tiller","meanings":["English (southern, especially Hampshire): occupational name from Middle English <i>tiliere</i>, <i>tilyer</i> ‘one who tills the soil, husbandman, farmer, farm laborer’. This is a derivative of Old English <i>tilian</i> ‘to till (the soil)’, Middle English <i>tilie</i>. There has been some confusion of this name with   Tyler  .","German: variant of <b>Tüller</b> (see   Tuller  )."]},{"name":"Tiley","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire, Somerset and Wiltshire): variant of   Tilley  ."]}]},{"name":"Mother","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Mothers  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mothers","meanings":["English: (i) relationship name, nickname probably from the Old Scandinavian personal name  <i>Móðir</i>,  <i>Modher</i>, with post-medieval excrescent  <i>-s</i>. (ii) however, the form of 1279 is clearly the Middle English word  <i>moder</i> ‘mother’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mother Tilley was born about 1062, i